<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission from the Federation of Master Builders – written evidence</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," width="81" height="115" alt="FMB Sign of Building Qual low res" style="margin-left:468.75pt; margin-top:-57.35pt; position:absolute; z-index:0" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Submission from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Federation of Master Builders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> – written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ABOUT THE FEDERATION OF MASTER BUILDERS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Federation of Master Builders (FMB) is the largest trade association in the UK building industry. Established in 1941 to protect the interests of small and medium-sized</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (SME)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> construction firms, the FMB is independent and non-profit-making, lobbying continuously for members’ interests at both national and local levels.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FMB is a source of knowledge, professional advice and support for its members, providing a range of modern and relevant business services to save them time and money. The FMB also offers practical advice and support to the general public on choosing and working with a builder.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">BACKGROUND</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public sector construction contracts are worth more than £37bn per year, which is a considerable 38% of all construction output. However, although small firms dominate the construction industry in terms of both output and employment, this is not usually reflected in the success rate of SMEs when tendering for public sector contracts. According to our research, 41% of construction SMEs are only successful 10% of the time or less when bidding for public sector contracts and a significant 55% of firms have seen their success rate decrease over the past five years.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In March and April 2013, the FMB surveyed its members in England on their experiences of the public procurement process. The survey received more than 450 responses and the results have been analysed and discussed with a working group of FMB members with experience of public sector procurement. This information then formed the basis of a research report with sixteen recommendations to central government, local government and the wider public sector, as well as to industry itself. The report was published in June 2013 and the full version can be viewed </span><a href="https://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;ved=0CD8QFjAB&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.fmb.org.uk%2FEasySiteWeb%2FGatewayLink.aspx%3FalId%3D796956&amp;ei=fNFSUoDWF8ar0AXh84DwBQ&amp;usg=AFQjCNF2xg_VuGObSUt24Dk0zP3JoWxW9A&amp;sig2=owQ4XS5KDwC678L05"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">here</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The findings of the report have helped form the basis for this written evidence submission to the CLG Select Committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">FMB members are typically micro-businesses employing ten or fewer employees and therefore most are not suited to working on central government contracts. Of those members that do engage with public sector clients, most work for local authorities or housing associations. Therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the CLG Select Committee inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local government procurement is o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f great interest and most welcome. However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the headline topics and questions laid out in the call for evidence are not ones that the FMB can easily respond. In light of this, this paper provides a few key points under the areas that are of particular interest to small construction firms – namely the pre-qualification process; framework agreements; the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">performance of public sector procurement teams; visibility of local authority contracts; and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transparency and accountability.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">LOCAL GOVERNMENT PROCUREMENT – KEY ISSUES</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Pre-qualification process</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although Pre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-qualification Questionnaires (PQQs) are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an integral part of the supplier assessment process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, their introduction has had the unintended consequence of increasing the cost and time burden on SMEs and thus, in many cases, reducing their access to public sector contracts.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Almost half of all those members responding to the FMB’s public procurement survey describe their experience of completing PQQs for public sector clients as being “quite negative” or “mostly negative”.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Key points include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FMB fully supports the recent Cabinet Office proposal to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eliminate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the use of PQQs for low value contracts, mandating a core PQQ with standard questions for high value contracts, and allowing suppliers to provide PQQ data only once;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FMB also supports the “only once” approach whereby a single online system for verification and display of PQQ data is used. This would save SMEs a great deal of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">valuable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> time and make bidding for public sector contracts more attractive as each time the contracting authority goes out to tender, the standard PQQ information is already there. Clearly construction SMEs would be responsible for updating their data at regular intervals and automatic reminders could be issued to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this happens;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As stated in the FMB’s research report, all public sector clients, including local authorities, should use PAS 91 (2013) as the basis for their construction PQQs and central government should do more to properly promote, to the wider public sector, the benefits of using PAS 91. A more generic PQQ would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be suitable for procuring from construction firms and should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be used for local authority construction contracts;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It would be helpful if one single online platform/scheme was used for managing, submitting and verifying construction PQQ responses. It would help keep costs down for construction SMEs that are currently being asked to join a number of pre-qualification schemes, all of which they must pay to register with and then spend time submitting the same core information;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, we understand the concerns of some local authorities about the cost and time involved in maintaining such a system and ensuring all suppliers’ details are kept up to date. Therefore, in the absence of a single online platform for managing construction PQQ information, we support the use of regional online portals to register suppliers’ PQQ data providing the standard construction PQQ is used and there is no cost for businesses to access these portals and register their information. The North East Procurement Organisation (NEPO) is an example of one regional online portal currently being used to manage PQQ data.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Framework agreements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Construction SMEs accept that, as part of the public sector’s desire to reduce construction costs by 2015, framework agreements will continue to be used as a means by which to help deliver so-called efficiency savings and reduce consultancy and construction costs. However, it is clear that framework agreements are perceived as a barrier to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">construction </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SMEs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> attempt to win public sector work, with 51% of FMB members reporting that their workloads have decreased as a result of the introduction of frameworks. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Key points include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many FMB members report that they are often rejected for work under a framework agreement because </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are being overly cautious when assessing a firm’s capacity to deliver, particularly when it comes to points being awarded based on a firm’s turnover.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Therefore local authorities should review the limitations they impose when assessing the financial viability of SMEs attempting to get on to a framework. Councils should emulate the approach taken by the private sector and deem a construction SME firm’s turnover to be suitable in all cases where the contract is no more than 33% of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the firm’s annual turnover;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where framework agreements make it impossible for smaller firms to become the principal contractor, it is essential to be part of the supply chain in order to access the market. However, this is not always easy according to construction SMEs in general and micro-businesses in particular. FMB members report that main contractors are often less willing to deal with good, experienced smaller firms and prefer to sub-contract to those that will accept almost any terms and conditions dictated by the main contractor, such as poor payment practices. Local authorities should mandate, via the contract terms, the payment of the Tier 2 contractor by the Tier 1 contractor within 30 days to help ensure fair payment principles become a real</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ity throughout the supply chain;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities should desist from the wholesale ‘bundling’ of contracts to increase opportunities for SMEs to act as principal contractors on smaller contracts, and use their influence to ensure fair access and payment practices are applied throughout the supply chain;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FMB is currently working with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills on a new ‘Fair Payment Charter’ for construction which will include a recommendation on how public sector clients can help enforce fair and prompt payment through the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">extended</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> supply chain. This must be finalised and implemented, with the strong backing of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government, as soon as possible;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">properly examine the benefits of rolling out the use of Project Bank Accounts (PBAs) for all construction contracts over the value of £1 million. There is evidence to suggest that this is an extremely effective means by which to ensure the whole supply chain is paid promptly, rather than the main contractor only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order to overcome some of the additional barriers created by the use of framework agreements, there are some examples of smaller firms coming together to form consortia in order to improve their chances. However, this model will not suit every construction SME, particularly micro-businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as the associated legal and professional costs of setting one up will be disproportionate when compared to the value of the contracts they are typically suited to.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Performance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">local authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> procurement teams</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public sector spending cuts have significantly reduced the amount of resource available to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and this is most likely to have increased pressure on their procurement processes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore than 260,000 jobs have been lost in local government since 2010 through redundancies and the deletion of vacant posts</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and more cuts are imminent.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One impact of this lack of resource available to public sector bodies, particularly local authorities, is the limited supply of feedback to those who are unsuccessful, which is a commonly cited problem by construction SMEs. However, FMB research shows that, in terms of local authorities, 50% of respondents describe the expertise of the procurement staff as being “average” and 22% describe them as “good” or “excellent”. Further still, 44% of FMB members stated that local authority procurement teams adhere to statutory timescales for responses “most of the time” and 9% said that this is “always” the case.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite this, there are concerns about the provision of detailed and timely feedback to unsuccessful bidders in the procurement process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Key points include:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Construction SMEs accept that, due to fair competition, they will not win every public sector contract they bid for. However, when they are not successful, they do require timely and constructive feedback from the relevant procurement team to ensure that, when they are a genuinely suitable option, they are doing all that they can to demonstrate this f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">act to the public sector client;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Unfortunately, feedback is not always effectively communicated by public sector clients, if at all. For instance, 27% of those FMB members responding to the survey reported that local authorities “sometimes” adhere to proposed and/or statutory timescales for responses and 21% stated that this is “rarely” or “never” their experience of receiving feedback;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More concerning still, 40% of respondents reported that they “rarely” receive advice or feedback from a local authority regarding their participation in the procurement process and 19% “never” receive such feedback;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, this could in some cases be down to construction SMEs firms failing to realise that, under the EU Remedies Directive 2009, they are entitled to such feedback. Having said that, some FMB members report that they have failed to receive feedback even when it has been requested;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FMB strongly believes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all local authority procurement teams should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensure that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> detailed written feedback to unsuccessful firms that request such feedback, within 15 days of receiving a request.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Visibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> of local authority contracts</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For construction SMES, particularly micro-businesses that have little or no administrative support, it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s essential that they can find out about public sector contracts quickly and easily.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Key points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FMB agrees that opportunities worth more than £10,000 should be advertised in an easily accessible online forum. However, rather than using Contracts Finder to advertise public sector contracts all in one place, public sector clients should use their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">regional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> online portal to advertise opportunities to buyers. This would allow construction SMEs to search for contracts from a range of local authorities in their region, without having to search a potentially unwieldy nation-wide site. This is an approach favoured by many local authorities and some of the regional online portals currently being used include:</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">North East: </span><a href="http://www.qtegov.com"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.qtegov.com</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">North West: </span><a href="http://www.thechest.nwce.gov.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.thechest.nwce.gov.uk</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">South West: </span><a href="http://www.supplyingthesouthwest.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.supplyingthesouthwest.org.uk</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">South East: </span><a href="http://www.businessportal.southeastiep.gov.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.businessportal.southeastiep.gov.uk</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London: </span><a href="http://www.londontenders.org"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.londontenders.org</span></a></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Therefore, to summarise, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the FMB would like to see all local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">use their regional online portal to advertise opportunities to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">suppliers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">above the value of £10,000.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Transparency and accountability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FMB believes that greater transparency in relation to the proportion of SME firms that local authorities and other public sector clients procure from, would gradually increase SME engagement. It would boost the proportion of work being awarded to SME firms by providing the star performers with positive feedback and media attention (such as the newly introduced ‘best councils to do business with’ awards) and the worst performers with negative feedback. It is likely to create a sense of healthy competition among neighbouring local authorities and drive up performance across the board.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Key points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> FMB believes that if the Tier 1 contractors were required to supply the public sector client with data on the payment of their own suppliers, a positive culture change would ensue. As before, the FMB believes strongly that greater transparency will lead to better payment outcomes for construction SMEs. It would also allow the public sector client to make informed decisions on which main contractors they would procure from in future, potentially discounting those that do not pay their suppliers on time and favouring those that do.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">UNISON press release, End the squeeze on Local Government (19th March 2013)</span></p></body></html>